Goal: {{ goal }}

Based on this information and files you find on the repository, or information about the ticket,
decide how to divide up the discovery phase of the workflow.

Fan-out policy:
- Submit ALL discovery agent requests in a single response.
- Default to exactly 1 discovery agent request unless the goal is truly complex and can be split into non-overlapping discovery tracks.
- If you fan out (>1), include clear delegation rationale explaining why 1 agent is insufficient.
- Do not defer or omit any discovery request that is necessary to fully understand the codebase for the goal.

Execution order:
- Discovery agents run **sequentially**, not in parallel — each agent receives the results of all prior agents in its prompt context.
- Order your requests so that foundational/infrastructure discovery runs first and higher-level/orchestration discovery runs later, building on earlier findings.
- Later agents can reference and refine earlier agents' conclusions rather than re-discovering the same information.

Scope coordination:
- When fanning out to multiple discovery agents, define clear non-overlapping scope for each request.
- Each request should include `priorAgentSummary` describing what earlier agents found and what to NOT re-discover.
- This prevents looping and ensures knowledge compounds across sequential agent invocations.

View-aware scoping:
- The repository has 15 pre-built mental model views under `views/`. Each discovery agent can query these for structured analysis using the view-agent-exec system.
- Available views: acp-module, agent-execution, agent-framework, api-layer, artifact-key, event-messaging, filter-propagation, graph-nodes, mcp-server-client, orchestration-model, persistence, prompts, testing, ui-tui, utility-module.
- When defining each agent's scope, mention which views are relevant to their subdomain focus. The agent will use these to accelerate discovery via pre-analyzed source code maps.

